        <h2 class='stockHeadline'>Getting Started with Investing</h2>
        <div class='definition'>
            <p>Definition:</p>
            <p>Investing is the act of allocating resources, usually money, with the expectation of generating an income or profit. It is a key component of building wealth and achieving financial goals. Understanding the basics of investing is crucial for making informed decisions.</p>
        </div>
        <div class='understandingStocks'>
            <h2>Why Invest?</h2>
            <p>Investing allows you to put your money to work and potentially grow it over time. Here are some reasons why investing is important:</p>
            <ol id='list'>
                <li>Wealth Building:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investing can help grow your wealth over the long term.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Inflation Protection:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investing can protect your money from the eroding effects of inflation.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Income Generation:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investments can provide a regular income stream through dividends or interest payments.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Retirement Planning:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investing is essential for building a retirement fund to ensure financial security in your later years.</li>
                </ul>
            </ol>
            <h2 class = >Types of Investments</h2>
            <p>There are various types of investments, each with its own risk and return profile. Some common types include:</p>
            <ol id='list'>
                <li>Stocks:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Represent ownership in a company and offer potential for high returns but also come with higher risk.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Bonds:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Debt securities that provide regular interest payments and are generally less risky than stocks.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Mutual Funds:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Pooled funds managed by professionals, offering diversification and reduced risk compared to individual stocks.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Real Estate:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Involves purchasing property to generate rental income or capital appreciation.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>ETFs (Exchange-Traded Funds):</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Similar to mutual funds but trade on stock exchanges, offering liquidity and diversification.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Commodities:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Physical assets like gold, oil, and agricultural products, providing diversification and a hedge against inflation.</li>
                </ul>
            </ol>
            <h2>Investment Strategies</h2>
            <p>Choosing the right investment strategy is crucial for achieving your financial goals. Some common strategies include:</p>
            <ol id='list'>
                <li>Value Investing:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Focuses on buying undervalued stocks with strong fundamentals.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Growth Investing:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Focuses on companies expected to grow at an above-average rate.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Income Investing:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Focuses on stocks that provide regular income through dividends.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Index Investing:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Involves investing in index funds that track a specific market index, offering broad market exposure and lower costs.</li>
                </ul>
                <li>Dollar-Cost Averaging:</li>
                <ul>
                    <li>Investing a fixed amount regularly, regardless of market conditions, to reduce the impact of volatility.</li>
                </ul>
            </ol>
        </div>
        <div class='takeaway'>
            <h2>Takeaway</h2>
            <p>Getting started with investing requires understanding the basics, including the different types of investments and strategies available. By educating yourself and developing a clear plan, you can begin your investment journey with confidence and work towards achieving your financial goals.</p>
        </div>
